			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I can't help but agree with this article.  <img src="images/smiles/wig.gif" alt="wig" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.02/start.html?pg=2?tw=wn_tophead_5" target="_blank">http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.02/start.html?pg=2?tw=wn_tophead_5</a>
<br />

<br />
Seriously, have you see the @#%$ that passes for patents these days? I'm begining to think patents and copyright should simply be done away with in their entirety. I don't see any value for them in an information age. The public domain chaos that ensues will be far better (and far more productive) than the crap we endure now. Put your mind in forward mode and think about where all these developments are leading over the next twenty years.
<br />

<br />
So what if some genius comes up with an engineering idea and then cannot patent it? To hell with him. I'm getting sick and tired of the "idea" guys getting all the money and credit in the current system. I think the money and the credit ought to be going to the people who take that idea and USE it for something rather than sitting on it like some kind of hoarded nest egg. Let the ones who use the ideas and technology to actually do something get the rewards. The idea guy has first dibs on this beacuse it's HIS idea dna he's the first to know it, but if he doesn't move on it, he's got nobody to blame except himself for his failure to capitalize. In that situation everything intellectual is open to everyone, owned by no one, controlled by no one, and those who can use all this information the most effectively are the ones who come out on top.
<br />

<br />
That @#%$ about "innovation" dying because nobody can afford to do any research is just that, pure @#%$. The ones making the money will do the research because that's still the only way to progress in those fields, and if they don't, someone else will and they will get a leg up on those who don't. Innovation will hit an all time high because all the red tape that strangles the life out of it will be gone for good. It'll become something anyone can do without fear of stepping on some useless intellectual property laws and getting sued for the mere act of thinking.
<br />

<br />
So what if an artist makes music and then can't profit on the trade of it on the internet? Let them make it because they like it. They'll be able to make money from concerts if they are any good, and they'll earn plenty of respect and recognition from the folks who like it. Same goes for any artist or inventor. Artists make art because they just do. Compensation is not a prerequisite to art (sure, it helps, but it's not and shouldn't be the sole reason for the art).
<br />

<br />
Patents and Copyrights were all well and good in their time, but today they are holding us back. It's time for a sea change in thinking, and the entire concept of intellectual property needs to be done away with completely. This change is inevitable, it's going to happen no matter what people do. We can either be the ones to embrace it and benefit from it or the ones who are left behind when it happens elsewhere.
<br />

<br />
I've had enough of the lies about patents being the only way to ensure disclosure of manufacturing processes and scientific ideas or methods as well. What good is this disclosure? Nobody else is permitted to use it, so it's about as useful as putting your lunch in a sealed glass box and saying you can look but you can't eat it. What's the difference, really, between a company not disclosing a manufacturing process to keep it secret and a company who does disclose it, but no one else is allowed to use it or anything like it (at least without paying a huge fee to license)? We can do better than that.
<br />

<br />
The only danger I see in that system is people taking credit for another's ideas or creations, because the respect and recognition gained from good ideas and good creations becomes the only reward one can get in that system. The respect and recognition can themselves lead to financial gains, but money isn't guaranteed. As long as some form of registry is kept in place so that the original inventor is recognized, all is well and good.
<br />

<br />
And to hell with the lawyers. They are the only ones making a profit on this mess because their involvement is necessary at every step of the way. You will never see the legal profession lift a finger to fix this sytem because they all have far too much to gain from it staying exactly the way it is. Solve this IP problem and you will go a long way towards fixing some of the biggest problems with what passes for law in this country. Any such reform won't come from the legal system or the government; it'll be actively opposed by both of them as well as most corporations. It looks to me like this is a change that america is incapable of making. That means the think tank of the world won't be here for much longer. I'm thinking it's headed back to the east, over to India and China, whose time it appears is finally coming after all.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
