			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				While I agree with some of the things you said,  sitting on a patent wouldn't be terribly effective.  Usually takes several years to get a patent, during that time it sits in "patent pending".  However, after a certain time in patent pending status your idea is released and can be copied by the general public.  So if you patent an idea and don't do anything with it, after a while someone can take and use your idea until your patent is approved.  After that, you can try to take legal action but the courts in the past haven't been to cooperative with those who don't do anything with the idea/product while it's in patent pending status.
<br />
What i find interesting is that a lot of patents are based on a process rather than the final product.  Like pharmaceuticals,  there are currently several companies working on a pill identical to Viagra, yet they can get around patents because they used a different method of creating it.
<br />

<br />
-Imirik<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
