			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Sitting on patents is all that corporations do anymore. IBM's patent portfoli is a thing of legend, and any time they get miffed at someone they nail them with a handful of patent lawsuits, since there is literally no business you can be in that does not infringe on some patent owned by IBM in some way. 
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/03/08/07/HNibmlawsuit_1.html" target="_blank">http://www.infoworld.com/article/03/08/07/HNibmlawsuit_1.html</a>
<br />

<br />
While I agree with your assesment of personal inventors, the courts behave very differently when dealing with a company that is sitting on patents. The majority of patents are held by companies now, and they can afford to sit on things forever if necessary. Some even patent things they never intend to use just to prevent their competitors from going in a certain direction.
<br />

<br />
 Just take a look at the dozens of highly publicized and very ridiculous patent lawsuits in the last few years. Patents are now a weapon used to strike down competitors and extort money from corporations. It's crazy. On top of that, you have people at the patent office approving patents that should not ever be approved... for example, just recently someone got a patent (they filed it in 2001) on the domain naming system (you know, site.subdomain.domain) that has been around since 1970 when the US Military invented the internet. That's the clearest case I've ever seen of the patent office with its head miles up its %@$#. The USPTO is reaching WTF? levels of stupidity.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.geek.com/news/geeknews/2004Jan/gee20040120023507.htm" target="_blank">http://www.geek.com/news/geeknews/2004Jan/gee20040120023507.htm</a>
<br />

<br />
Again, it can only be solved in court, and only the lawyers can benefit from it. All one has to do is sue someone with shallow pockets for patent infringement, and they've really got no choice but to settle since they can't afford the legal fees. It doesn't matter if the patent is clearly garbage, because only those with deep pockets can afford to pay the legal system to have it declared garbage and invalidated.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
