				<div class="postbody">
				I think that's no coincidence too. Tech is the fastest moving industry, and tech is also the only industry that has products that do not physically exist. What you are seeing here is what you would be seeing in all aspects of the real world if we had the equivalent of star-trek style replicators that could duplicate physical objects and real property the way computers can duplicate intellectual property. Nice to know that by the time we have the replicator technology, we'll already have a working paradigm (well, one can hope) for economics and social behaviour from what arises out of this stage in the information age. It's fundamentally the same problem.
<br />

<br />
Another possible (even probable) outcome from this is that only the copy-lefted technologies and artworks will last, with the patented and copyrighted closed works simply becoming unused or forgotten and therefore worthless. It's an effective way to completely end-around the entire system and avoid the legal and licensing problems altogether. It's the best thing going for the little guy.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
