<br />
This is rather amusing, considering the number one web server software (apache), number one server operating system (linux), number one email system (sendmail), and number one name service stack (bind) are all open source products. With such low productivity they should have easily been overtaken by commercial alternatives by now, but strangely the commercial alternatives are consistently of poorer quality and smaller featureset than the free alternatives. This is proven fact.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Im not saying open source is going to die but if you think people who produce and create are going to continue putting things out to the public domain for free very long you are mistaken. All of that material was donated to man as charity and people are only charitable when they have the resources to do so. Let programmers go hungry for a while and the charity comes to a screeching halt. 
