<br />

<br />
I'd love to see some examples of open source projects stalling due to lack of funds. They came from nothing, and were far more likely to fail back during those early days than they are now. The longer a project lives, the less likely it is to ever die. If anything the development process is going to accellerate a thousandfold when India and China come on board later this year and throughout next year. They will greatly increase the developer base for open applications.
<br />

<br />
See, the reason communism fails in the real world is because when I take from you, you no longer have something. In the digital world, where the cost of a copy is zero, when I take from you I have left you with everything you had and I have enriched myself. This is even better if you have the same ability to take from me to enrich yourself. A respect system is firmly in place that encourages those who benefit from the community to give back to it, and those wishing to gain that respect even for selfish reasons still must contribute to earn it. One can of course choose not to contribute, but this does not diminish the whole in any way. Many do choose to contribute; more, in most cases, than are necessary to perfect a given project, especially a popular one.
<br />

<br />
These boards are an open source application. People go to Tym's website for his code modules.
<br />

<br />
It's like the town commons economic theory, except that the more cows you have grazing, the faster the grass grows and the more of it there is to go around. It turns conventional economics completely around, and is obviously a superior development methodology, as has been proven dozens of times over the last few years.
<br />

<br />
Educate yourself on the way these things really work. Also don't make the mistake of thinking open source is public domain... it isn't, in fact, and it forbids many kinds of uses that are allowed for public domain materials. Raymond sums the whole thing up far better than I could, and I'd say he's been proven at least mostly right by current events. You'll be seeing Linux commercials this year at superbowl halftime courtesy of IBM. Five years ago I was arguing with idiots who didn't think linux would survive because it had no hardware support and you needed a PhD in gizmos to get the thing installed and running. Today it's the number one software in the world in several categories, and it is a household term.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.catb.org/~esr/writings/cathedral-bazaar/" target="_blank">http://www.catb.org/~esr/writings/cathedral-bazaar/</a>
<br />

<br />
You'll note that Patents have no place in this system, and if anything are a threat to the way it works, due to their ability to impede developments that occur naturally in this process. Patents are an industrial idea, and they are no longer fit to function in an information society. Any system that slows down the adoption or use of a good idea is a threat.
<br />

