So essentially you are saying that you agree with me; the incompetence of the patent office is causing problems in open, unrestricted development of new technologies and clogging the courts with useless, @#%$ lawsuits, as well as providing an easy way for the big guy to push the little guy around. Thanks. (For the record, I'm not interested in the Patent office or government's excuses or reasons, I'm only interested in their effects.)
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> You will see more and more programmers stop working on programming and start working at steer manuer shoveling as the lack of payment for their creative work drives them to other things in order to feed their families, keep rain off their heads, get an education, etc... etc.. etc... </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Many a star programmer got his experience, recognition, and current job by contributing to open source projects while in school or unemployed. You are confusing the effects of outsourcing programming overseas with the maturity of the open source movement. The two are utterly unrelated phenomenon. Open source programmers do get paid to write open source; look at anyone working for Mandrake, Red Hat, SuSE, or IBM. IBM is being sued right now for the large amounts of code they *paid* to have developed and released into Linux. There is plenty of money in open source; many companies offer large sums of money to have a programmer extend an open application in a way that benefits them. They are paying for a product they need but then sharing the result of that product with everyone. This should be tax deductible. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Look at the Linux distributions. They have added non open source pieces to linux to make it suitable to enterprise. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Please cite these non-open pieces of code. You can't, because they don't exist. Mandrake is 100% GPL, SuSE is 99.99% GPL, with YaST being the only non-GPL component, but Yast IS licensed under a valid open source license... one that simply prevents commercial competitiors from taking it and using it in their products. RedHat has made some interesting design changes lately that are alienating some of the community, but you can still get the source code for everything they have without paying for it. If you want it for free you simply use <a href="http://fedora.redhat.com/" target="_blank" class="postlink">fedora</a> or <a href="http://www.whiteboxlinux.org/" target="_blank" class="postlink">whitebox</a> Linux. Any attempt to close off an open project fails in a similar manner, with open derivatives appearing and the majority of the developer base shifting to the open fork.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> There are no real distributions that set up easily and cleanly, because that is where the profit is in support.  As time goes on the distributions will design themselves into more support reliant configurations and less and less of the actual distribution or stitching it together will be open source. The core will be open source but in time as charity dwindles and "feeding the kids" becomes more important to people it will happen more. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
SuSE, Mandrake, and RedHat all install without much effort; they are no more difficult to install than Windows XP or Windows Server depending on what you are trying to do. Distros that are not easy to set up and install (such as Debian, Gentoo, Slackware, etc) still exist and are still popular, but are not commercial. The facts indicate that commercial distros are easier to install than free ones, and continue to become easier to install and use with each release.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Just like communism it has this myth surrounding it that it will end patents (compare class struggle) period and is a tool to bring down the giant corprations which is absurd. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It destroys their revenue stream, so yes, it will most definitely lay low any corporation that gets in the way. Take a look at the corpses of the myriad unix corporations that have been annihilated by the rise of Linux if you want proof. If linux becomes good enough, it'll destroy the competition in all desktop environments as well, most likely within the next ten years. It'll happen when Microsoft's license agreements and upgrade costs for the new version tick off a critical mass of users, probably with Longhorn's release in 2006. 
<br />

<br />
It's a simple choice... you can have this thing, for free, or this other thing, for a price. Your learning curve is the same, your upkeep costs are the same. The free one gives you more freedom, costs nothing, and has community support from millions. The other one costs a lot and restricts your freedom, and support costs you a lot of money. That's a pretty stacked choice.
<br />

<br />
Any information or object that reaches a near-zero copy cost will follow this paradigm.
<br />

<br />
It may be that money cannot be made on open applications; as linux rises so will google's base of knowledge about it, and it's already enough to replace pay-for support for any competent technician. The inability to make money, however, does not affect the existence or acceptance of the open application. If it did, they never would have existed in the first place. The one place money can always be made, however, is in extending and improving the open applications. Do you see the simplicity, freedom, and danger inherent in this paradigm now?<br />
