			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				The idea behind patents and copyright isn't bad, but it's current implementation is seriously flawed.  Take the SCO threats against Linux users.  The hooplah this caused has probably set back hundreds of Linux companies by billions of dollars of total revenue this year.  Look at the patent office and check out the spurious patents that have been approved.
<br />

<br />
The concept of inventors, writers, artists and musicians retaining the exlusive rights to their inventions for a limited lenght of time is a good incentive to produce their works.  The current system whereby every time Mickey Mouses copyright is about to expire, Disney cons the government to extend the limitations on copyright is a bad idea.  Copyright and patent ad infinitum is an abhorent idea at best.  Imagine paying royalties on the Pythagorean theorem to the descendents of Pythagoras?  Productivity stagnates.  At some point in time, that so called 'intellectual property' becomes the property of humanity in general.
<br />

<br />
The granting of monopolies to produce a product should come with a cost.  Part of that cost is the research and work it takes to create the first copy of that product.  The other cost is that the monopoly must be time limited.  Should Leonardo Davinci's descendents hold a perpetual patent on the Helicopter?  Should Bell hold perpetual rights to the Telephone?  These inventions were pretty much destined to be discovered by someone - the story of the Telephone having two inventors shows that.
<br />

<br />
Patenting the obvious should not be allowed.  Unfortunately, pooly paid government employees who are probably overworked end up making the decisions.  I suppose there's a remedial process available, but you wouldn't know it from all the stories in the press about spurious patents and odious lawsuits that they spawn.  Sadly, those who can't afford the legal costs have no option but to give in to such bullies.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
