		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=48327&amp;sid=8881569249c4ee34191a070e86a27ff3#48327"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Feb 03, 2004 4:30 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Latest batch of american idiocy...</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=48327&amp;sid=8881569249c4ee34191a070e86a27ff3"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I maintain that patents will not be killed by public license but rather be improved by it. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I'd say they will either be killed by it or forced to improve by it. One or the other is definitely going to happen. This improvement will surely happen fifty years too late for it to do any good, and there will be myriad examples of scum paying for patents on open ideas that they did not invent, and then using that patent to selectively push around those who can't afford to fight them in a court of law.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> You complain that Amazon owns a patent for a shopping cart system? Know what, thats exactly what they own, and they buit a chunk of economy doing it. They took an idea and bloomed it into a massive company that proovided a basic service and was an archetype for internet commerce. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No. They built nothing. They <span style="font-weight: bold">stole</span> a public idea (using existing public code, even) and then used it to bully their competitors. Welcome to the way the patent system really works these days. They took a common practice that was being used by literally dozens of websites on the internet and patented it despite its widespread use, simply because nobody had patented it before. They then used this patent to bully around several other online venues who had been using similar one click systems and forced them under threat of lawsuit to change their systems into something less convenient for the shopper.
<br />

<br />
I suppose you still support a patent system that gives someone the right to do this.  
<br />

<br />
The plaintiff must show only evidence of infringement. The burden of proof rests with the defendant, who must show with prior art that the patent is invalid in order to defend himself. This isn't really that difficult, especially for the more ridiculous patents like the DNS Patent and Amazon's One-Click patent, but the catch is this: You still have to spend your time and energy (and money) in court, and that's very expensive. Little guys will settle rather than fight, and most of the time the kinds of people with these abusive patents don't pick on the guys who can afford to fight back. <a href="http://www.silicon.com/management/itpro/0,39024675,39117803,00.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">(Except in this case.)</a>
<br />

<br />
Several open-source legal funds have arisen lately to fight this sort of thing, though they are currently untested. The presence of these funds shows that it is a very common problem, a big one, and a threat to open business models. The point is they shouldn't have to defend themselves in the first place. The only reason they have to is because the current patent office is wholly, ubelievably incompetent at doing its job. The patent office reserves the right to do all prior art research, and they've shown they don't understand many types of patents well enough to recognize prior art if it kicked them down a flight of stairs. I won't hear excuses on why... I don't care if they are understaffed, underfunded, stupid, whatever... there is an important job there that needs doing and it's not getting done. Fix it, because blame is pointless and excuses are a poor attempt to ignore the problem.
<br />

<br />
It's only going to get worse because new ideas are coming in at an exponentially increasing rate. What do we do when the office is a full ten years behind the industry? Suddenly you owe licensing fees on an idea that everyone accepted as open ten years ago? That's laughably unacceptable.
<br />

<br />
Fix or remove. I vote remove, since fixing something we no longer need is rather pointless. I'd love to see someone come up with a working version of how to fix it, but so far nobody has any ideas that stand up to even a moment's scrutiny.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
