			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Thats because you want everything to be free.  Someone else does the work, you get the profit.
<br />

<br />
You have yet to address why patents exist in the first place much less deal with how that would be affected. You make a blithe dismissal thta creative people would create anyway.  I have 200 years of history that shows that innovation was increased in countries with patent systems and countries without them lost their creative people.
<br />

<br />
I have creative people like Franklin, Samuel Clemons and Thomas Jefferson writing extolations on the idea of patents.  You have some middle class socialist brats ranting how everything should be free for the taking.
<br />

<br />
Money represents production.  The act of developing a product costs money.  If the developer has no garuntee in recouping his expenditure: Not only does he not have a motivation to spend his time on "new and novel" ways of doing things, but he would be throwing good money after bad.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
As for your Amazon example. Bigger companies muscling out smaller less productive competitors is part of the game.  Again you don't get to have everyting nice and warm and fuzzy. You MUST produce to survive rather than coast on other peoples labors.  You must produce better than the other guy or he will destroy you.
<br />

<br />
That is not cruel, unusual or unproductive.  Mater of fact it is so productive a model that every competitive sport or game including EQ is modeled on the premise that competition means bullying for position (within the rules).
<br />

<br />
Tell me does Amazon still hold this patent or have there been enough instances of prior art that it is basicly invalidated as soon as it hits court?
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
Open source and Public License are being tossed around here like they are synonymous. They are not.  Open Source generally means source that is available for viewing and research.  It is an expectional idea.  I am also siding with the Germans in declaring that all software should be open source so that people can see what is REALLY going on if they have a need to.
<br />

<br />
Public License describes products that are released to the public domain (usually with some stipifiers) for general consumption.  That is the charity that I am talking about and the revolution that you are talking about.
<br />

<br />
However you view this revolution as a topping of patents. I see it as setting a minimum standard.  If the big boys do a lousey job (cough Microsloth) people doing charity work are going to out do them.
<br />

<br />
Linux did not blossum because giving away things that cost you resources to create is a good idea, it happened because the people rose up against monopolies that were seriously undermining the public trust.  I think that public license will continue to set a minimum standard.  Just like Government Cheese keeps the poor and indigent alive.
<br />

<br />
What's truely disgraceful is that Sun, Microsoft, HP, IBM and all those guys cut back on quality control and innovation so much that this phenomenon was able to shame them so quickly and easily.  In the case of OS's the government cheese tastes a heck of a lot better and is certainly more fulfilling than what you buy at a high priced restraunt.
<br />

<br />
In that analogy, I would not look to restraunts going away.  I would predict some restraunts going klunk, and others learning to cook with cheese and finding even better alternatives to draw customers in.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
