			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Texas Instruments was one of the inventors of the integrated circuit. They used to make all of their money manufacturing semiconductors (as well as calculators and computers). Nowadays 80% of their income is in licensing IP. When their patents expire, so will they. They could have spent the bucks to keep innovating like Intel or Motorola, but will fade away when their existing patents poof. 
<br />

<br />
There are many rediculous patents being issued. The patent office no longer tries to investigate whether they are original or not. They take the filing fees and let the folks with the deepest pockets duke it out in court. A common technique for enterprising folks is to dig up old dissertations from the 60s and 70s, file patent claims based on them and then sue everyone (and hope that no one can find the prior art). Dissertations in the 80s started to become available electronically, making that decade rather risky for this sort of trickery. 
<br />

<br />
Why was there no patent for waterbeds? Someone tried to patent one in the early 70s, but the patent examiner remembered reading a description of one in an old Heinlein novel from the 40s. That industry thrives without patent protection. So patents are not necessary for an industry to thrive. They can help, but one can live without them.
<br />

<br />
Another enterprising technique is to keep modifying the claims of your patent while it is being investigated by the patent office. This way, any changes in technology can be re-addressed in your claims, and the initial date that you filed the patent is what counts for filing lawsuits. The guy who claimed to invent single chip microprocessors did this, it took about 20 years from when the original claims were filed until the patent was actually issued. Because his original claims were in the system, all subsequent patent applications for single chip microprocessors were denied. They call these patents "submarine patents" because they appear out of nowhere, and sink whole industries with their 9 and 10 digit demands for royalties (per company). 
<br />

<br />
Companies usually try to beat down other companies' patents with a number of tricks, like claiming that it is obvious, or that prior art exists. Sometimes, they just prolong the legal shennanigans until the plaintiff has to drop their suit because they ran out of money. Microsoft likes to play that game, using other folks inventions and paying the 8 and 9 digit settlements out of petty cash, if the plaintiff lives that long.
<br />

<br />
Sample silly patents:
<br />
British Telecom claims to own a patent on hyperlinks.
<br />
Compton Multimedia claimed to own a patent on WWW and multimedia (patent revoked).
<br />
A patent for entering text by pressing buttons on the keypad of your phone. For example, to enter the letter F, press the 3 button 3 times. To enter the letter K, press the 5 button 2 times.
<br />
A patent for using CallerID to look up data in a computer.
<br />
A patent for putting navigation menus on the top or left of the screen. Optionally, the menus do not move off screen when the text is scrolled up and down. 
<br />

<br />
Patents can be useful for protecting your interests, if and only if you can afford the lawyers to defend your claims. Unfortunately the system is being gamed by folks who would rather use the legal system to deprive you of your patents, or to compel you to pay for someone elses invention. The system has lost the virtues that poppa was referring to. That system fizzled away and died in late 20th century. If the patent office were the same as it was in the early 70s, it would not be issuing these bogons: <span style="font-style: italic"> and we would not be having this discussion</span>. The myth about "inventing a better mousetrap and the world will beat a path to your door" never really existed. It is a nice ideal, and I wish it were close to true, but it is not, nor ever was. 
<br />

<br />
Amazon's patent was for 1-click shopping. They still have it. Barnes and Noble lost in court. Amazon doesn't own a patent for shopping carts, because there was too much prior art to get one for that. The 1-click patent had very little to do with their success, having a massive inventory and shipping it on time was what made them a better place to do business than B&N. B&N was more obsessed with buying up competing brick and mortar stores than in an online presence: wanting to be the only place you can buy a book at because all the other chains are part of the borg, and every store had the same inventory as each other. Almost all the market is taken up by Borders, B&N and Amazon. Independant bookstores are almost all gone: I predict they will vanish as the owners retire or die. Most college campus bookstores are actually owned by B&N.
<br />

<br />
IBM lost out on OS2 because Microsoft had better marketing. All the things that keep getting hyped as new and improved for windows were already in OS2 years before it was in NT4, Win9x, Win2kx, ME or XP. But the propaganda about "innovation" won out over the truth.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
