			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Thats because you want everything to be free. Someone else does the work, you get the profit. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Not quite. Everyone does the work, everyone gets the benefit (benefit is not necessarily profit). If every idea on the planet is open, the one who builds the best toys with those ideas win. The market becomes one of pure quality. Stop pretending that having all of these ideas open and royalty-free will prevent anyone from buying anything. Quality will drive the market, and the market will move faster than it has ever moved before, because the @#%$ red tape will simply be gone.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> You have yet to address why patents exist in the first place much less deal with how that would be affected. You make a blithe dismissal thta creative people would create anyway. I have 200 years of history that shows that innovation was increased in countries with patent systems and countries without them lost their creative people. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I don't care why they exist. I only care about the obvious damage they are doing. You've yet to respond to any of my points about how harmful the system is to open ideas. As for your 200 years of history, here's a news flash. It's about as relevant today as a phalanx of roman soldiers would be facing off against the US Army. The times have changed, the playing field is very different. Stop thumping on history books and use your mind.
<br />

<br />
I guarantee you that if you were to ask Sam Clements, Ben Franklin, and Thomas Jefferson about the state of the current patent and copyright systems, they would be absolutely horrified that their good work had been perverted into a tool to abuse the rights of individuals and lock up good ideas so that only the wealthy could profit. I can easily imagine Clements going off on a tirade about it. If introduced to the concept of these new open methods hitting the market, they would be stunned that people would be able or willing to cooperate on the scale necessary to make them work, and while I can't say for certain I'm sure they'd favor a system that increases the wealth of human knowledge and provides an economy based on quality over the system we currently have.
<br />

<br />
They'd still agree that those who invented the ideas should get some kind of benefit, and I don't disagree with that. I'm simply stating that we must find a way to make that work in an open system where the idea is free to all once created. The founding fathers might even have been able to see a way to do that; they would certainly be sympathetic to it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Money represents production. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No. Compensation for production comes in many forms. Say rather that production is represented by an enrichment of the lives of the producing parties, and money is the easiest way to do this at this time. It's a subtle difference but I think it is important. How do you assign a monetary value to the immense respect Linus has garnered for all the free work he did creating Linux? You can't really, but his life has been enriched by it. He earned an honorary Ph.D from U of Finland, and his resume guarantees him a job anywhere he goes looking for one. It wasn't monetary compensation, even though it puts him in a position to earn more monetary compensation than he would have otherwise been able to.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The act of developing a product costs money. If the developer has no garuntee in recouping his expenditure: Not only does he not have a motivation to spend his time on "new and novel" ways of doing things, but he would be throwing good money after bad. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I'm merely suggesting that a granted monopoly is the wrong form of compensation. I'm open to suggestions of other methods, but I'm not open to arguing about the utter stupidity of granting monopolies, especially those based on stolen open ideas.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> As for your Amazon example. Bigger companies muscling out smaller less productive competitors is part of the game. Again you don't get to have everyting nice and warm and fuzzy. You MUST produce to survive rather than coast on other peoples labors. You must produce better than the other guy or he will destroy you. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That argument has no relevance whatsoever on the Amazon issue. A clickable shopping system is not the product of that company, it's simply a mechanism they ripped off and patented for selling to customers. They are coasting on the labors of other people who were using similar sales systems. You are essentially defending their right to steal and patent public ideas and then use them to interfere with another competitors' ability to sell their product to their customers online.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> That is not cruel, unusual or unproductive. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Right, I forgot, this is America. We support legalized theft in this country.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Open source and Public License are being tossed around here like they are synonymous. They are not. Open Source generally means source that is available for viewing and research. It is an expectional idea. I am also siding with the Germans in declaring that all software should be open source so that people can see what is REALLY going on if they have a need to. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Open Source is simply the best example to date of a public license. The actual term "Open Source" means the source is <span style="font-weight: bold">freely</span> available to everyone. Free is the key here. Terms of use of that source vary from license to license.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Public License describes products that are released to the public domain (usually with some stipifiers) for general consumption. That is the charity that I am talking about and the revolution that you are talking about. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />
Dead wrong. Here's where your misunderstanding is shown. That which is in the public domain is free for anyone to use at any time without any strings attached, not even the need to put up a notice of its use. There are no rules of any kind governing its use. This is not what we want, because in that system there is no form of recognition for one's works and contributions. This is too loose, too free. There has to be some form of recognition, some requirement to at least acknowledge the works of the contributor whose work you are using.
<br />

<br />
The GPL is so successful because in addition to the recognition, it requires you contribute any further developments you make back into the pool of GPLed software unless you plan to use them only for yourself, privately. Have you thought for a moment how much this can cut down on the costs of R&amp;D? If your goal is 90% achieved by the open methods, you can either do that 90% of the work (and spend 90% more in cost) yourself so that you own the entire solution, or you can use the open method, add in that 10% it was missing for your purposes, and then release that 10% back to the community. You just saved 90% of your costs and increased the public knowledgebase at the same time. This is a win-win. The same concept can be applied to any market or industry; it is not restricted to computer code only.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> However you view this revolution as a topping of patents. I see it as setting a minimum standard. If the big boys do a lousey job (cough Microsloth) people doing charity work are going to out do them. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This minimum standard is slowly but surely enveloping everything in the software market. There are technologies arising from open source projects that totally outstrip their commercial competitors. Apache is the best example of this. How can the very best product be a "minimum standard" when nobody can hope to top it? In that system, nobody is ever going to bother to try; they'll just use the open solution and extend it to fit their needs. Your minimum standard has several hundred thousand times the developer base of any closed standard, and so no closed standard will ever be able to compete with it. Closed standards will eventually be crushed out of existence.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Linux did not blossum because giving away things that cost you resources to create is a good idea, it happened because the people rose up against monopolies that were seriously undermining the public trust. I think that public license will continue to set a minimum standard. Just like Government Cheese keeps the poor and indigent alive. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
It happened because there was an itch to scratch, as you say: A noticeable lack in quality computer software. That is not, however, the reason it continues to happen. The reason it continues to happen is because it is more efficient than commercial systems, and it saves businesses a whole lot of money. The freedom that comes with using it is a nice plus as well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> What's truely disgraceful is that Sun, Microsoft, HP, IBM and all those guys cut back on quality control and innovation so much that this phenomenon was able to shame them so quickly and easily. In the case of OS's the government cheese tastes a heck of a lot better and is certainly more fulfilling than what you buy at a high priced restraunt. In that analogy, I would not look to restraunts going away. I would predict some restraunts going klunk, and others learning to cook with cheese and finding even better alternatives to draw customers in. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Your scenario has a flaw. The restaraunts aren't going to be the victims of this revolution. The cheese vendors are.
<br />

<br />
If the government's cheese is so good, why bother trying to make a new kind of cheese? Any competing cheese vendors' innovations can easily be duplicated by the government in that scenario, so essentially the cheese vendor competition is all doomed to go out of business. If anyone wants a new kind of cheese, they'll draw upon the public resources to create it and release their new cheese back into the government pool. They'll have their new cheese, but so will everyone. Clearly, no money can be made creating new kinds of cheeses, so cheese creation becomes a matter of necessity (or, get this, art!) rather than profit. Different driving force, same result, cheaper R&amp;D since you can draw on the public base.
<br />

<br />
The money is being made by the restaraunts who use that cheese to create some exciting dishes. So what if the recipie for that dish is available to everyone? Sure, you can make it at home, but sometimes you just don't want to do the work of cooking. Sure, every restaraunt has their spin on dish x, but when word gets out that Cheezeorama has the best one, they are the one to make the buck. Now you've forced the restaraunts to compete on the quality and price of their dishes rather than the uniqueness of their recipies.
<br />

<br />
And the government cheese is still there if you don't need the variety and want to save money.
<br />

<br />
Look at what this means for the people: All the free cheese you can eat, new cheeses being discovered as they are needed or invented for fun by some well respected cheese geniuses, and a ton of really kickass restaraunts. There's also a lot of recognition to be had if you can advance the field and everyone is eating a dish using your cheese because it kicks %@$#.
<br />

<br />
These rules are not the rules of an industrial society. Not anymore.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
