	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="48624"></a><b>poppa</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">
		<br /><img class="avatar" src="http://www.hailcos.org/photos/poppa_60_60.GIF" alt="" /><br />
		<br />Joined: 23 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 346</span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=48624&amp;sid=8881569249c4ee34191a070e86a27ff3#48624"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Feb 05, 2004 2:16 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Latest batch of american idiocy...</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=48624&amp;sid=8881569249c4ee34191a070e86a27ff3"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I don't care why they exist. I only care about the obvious damage they are doing. You've yet to respond to any of my points about how harmful the system is to open ideas.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is the crux of what is blinding you.  You are arguing apples against oranges while Im just talking fruit.
<br />

<br />
The crux of my position is that patents as a concept and as they are efficiently used are a powerful engine for innovation and 200 years of history is damn good.
<br />

<br />
The current implementation of the patent process is too bulky and costly for most to traverse.  It is also dangerous because it threatens that which is in the public domain and discourages the openess of commecial source code so that people can rightfully see what those instructions sets are "really" doing with their private data.
<br />

<br />
I conceed all of that; However, I do not conceed that throwing the baby out with the bathwater is a viable solution.
<br />

<br />
The problem is that the patent office should be doing a better job at sorting for prior art.  I think that we should be pushing for an increase in that systems infrastructure and an overhaul of their processes. The fault lays in the courts and their inability to comprehend technology and adapt quickly to a changing information environment.  They are not doing a good job at judging what is novel and what is obvious.
<br />

<br />
That does not require that patents be thrown out.  Courts change slowly for a reason and to force quick change on them could have disasterous effects.  We have courts in order to slow knee-jerk reactions.
<br />

<br />
I think that a better solution to the dilemma you rail against is defendants being sued by the likes of Amazon that have patented something that is already in the publiic domain pooling together and breaking them with counter suits as a class action.
<br />

<br />
We are at a transitional time where innovation has taken off at a wildly accelerating pace.  There is tension because the courts and the market have not developed systems to deal with the new load.
<br />

<br />
It is the nature of the market to develop ways of dealing with the theives and the leeches and the courts will adapt as the landscape of the problem becomes more clear.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
